  "prompt": "What happens to your phlegm after swallowing it?",
  "response": "After swallowing phlegm, it travels down the esophagus and into the stomach. The stomach contains strong acids and enzymes that break down the phlegm, along with other ingested substances, as part of the digestive process. The broken-down components are further processed in the intestines, and any waste is eventually eliminated from the body. Swallowing phlegm is a normal and harmless process, as the body is designed to handle it this way.",
